On HIV, noncommunicable diseases in eight key points
GENEVA - Noncommunicable diseases (NCDs), such as cardiovascular diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, sedentary behavior, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the risk of premature death from NCDs.
Yet despite widespread awareness of these risks, global obesity is not generally controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
This context led to the convening of the partners networks for NCDs at the Second Global Forum of the Alliance for NCDs in the United Arab Emirates from December 9 to 11.
In their search for solutions to regulate NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the AIDS fight movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress achieved.
While the battle is not over, AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs could push back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NCD community as being "awaiting an electroshock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from the AIDS activism movement.
While global attention focuses on NCD prevention, those seeking to control avoidable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABCs of AIDS-fighting organizations.
The first letter the NCD community must consider is "A," as in activism.
Anyone over 40 certainly remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-in" protests at scientific meetings worldwide.
In the United States, AIDS activists have taken to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
At the global level, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the NCD Community must adopt a bolder approach to funding - the "B" of the AIDS fighting movement strategy.
Civil society and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energy, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires money.
The AIDS fighting movement was clear about this from the outset and pressured for resources to support its activities of awareness and empowerment effectively.
« C » represents the coalitions: the AIDS fighting movements did not take long to realize that progress comes only with multiple supporters.
Mobilizers have established links between people living with HIV and those concerned with other issues, such as women's rights, intellectual property, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns function better when they bring together internal and external leaders to the authorities, combining their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS fighting movement also understood that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential to spreading its support.
Thus, « D », the determining factor of success, consisted in 'highlighting the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying leaders in education to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make smart decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, connections have been made between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a key role in the AIDS crisis.
NCDs are no less isolated in their causality and also face a multi-sectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement - « E » - has been what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which defended the catchphrase "Nothing About Us Without Us," advocates for the AIDS cause demanded representation for the entities in place to treat the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Governing Board for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply integrated into the AIDS fight movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
Preventive disease movements must also develop convincing narratives, and « F » - framing the issue - is essential for the AIDS community to secure political leadership support.
In particular, access to AIDS treatment has been framed as an issue of economic justice.
Formulating the story this way has led to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the point where more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are now on treatment.
<s>Une formulation tout aussi importante de la question pour le SIDA, une question très pertinente pour le mouvement des MNT, est celle de la responsabilité.
<s>La communauté du SIDA a travaillé dur pour mettre davantage l'accent sur le choix de vie des personnes, plutôt que pour attribuer la responsabilité de l'État dans la prestation de soins de santé et dans la suppression de la discrimination légale.
<s>Dans le débat sur le SIDA, le genre - le « G » de notre mouvement - a été un point significatif.
<s>Le VIH était initialement considéré comme une « maladie des gays » et l'identité de genre s'est enracinée dès le début dans l'ADN du mouvement de lutte contre le SIDA.
<s>Les dimensions de genre de ces maladies ne sont pas moins importantes : il suffit d'examiner la façon dont l'alcool et le tabac sont commercialisés pour le comprendre.
<s>Le genre, par conséquent, doit devenir un foyer des efforts de prévention des MNT.
<s>Enfin, « H » - les droits de l'homme - sont le fondement de la riposte au SIDA.
<s>Des campagnes ont été lancées contre la discrimination sur les lieux de travail, dans les écoles et dans les centres médicaux.
<s>Le litige stratégique a permis d'assurer l'égalité en vertu de la loi.
<s>Le mouvement de lutte contre le SIDA a refusé de tenir des conférences majeures dans les pays ayant des lois répressives contre les personnes vivant avec le VIH.
The NCD movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit unhealthy food advertising to children.
We could continue the list of lessons learned from the AIDS fight alphabetically, but given that human rights provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases, we think it appropriate to close with "H".
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization, put people at greater risk for HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS advocacy movement clearly said that this question is not the right one.
Aujourd'hui, avec 70 % de la planète en danger de mort prématurée à cause de maladies évitables, « ces gens » représentent un grand nombre d'entre nous.
Les communautés des MNT et du SIDA peuvent apprendre l'une de l'autre.
Nous sommes un movement plus fort lorsque nous unissons nos forces.
Les opinions exprimées ici ne reflètent pas nécessairement celles de l'ONUSIDA.
